11. Enforcement Protocol




★

NEW IN v1.1 — Mandatory amendment. The doctrine previously used mandatory language with no defined enforcement mechanism. This section adds the process, authority, artefact, and consequence structure required to make the doctrine operational rather than aspirational.



A doctrine without enforcement is a memo. This section defines who enforces the standard, at what stage, through what artefact, and with what consequence. These are the teeth of the document.



11A — Gatekeeper Authority

Every design or engineering submission affecting a user-facing screen requires sign-off from both the Design Lead and the Engineering Lead for the relevant product area. Neither can approve unilaterally. Both must countersign the review checklist.



The CTO holds override authority. An override requires a written justification filed in the project's decision log within 24 hours of the override decision. Override justifications are reviewed at the next monthly doctrine review.



11B — Submission Process

Step

Actor

Required Artefact

SLA

Submit

Designer or Engineer

Completed Section 7 checklist attached as PDF or PR comment. Five-question walkthrough documented per screen.

At submission

Initial Review

Design Lead

Checklist verified line by line. No partial passes. Pass or return decision recorded in writing.

48 hours

Technical Review

Engineering Lead

State machine compliance, status enum use, audit hook presence verified against Section 12.

48 hours

Sign-off

Both Leads

Joint approval. Both names on the record. Code may not be merged until this step is complete.

24 hours post-review

Override (if needed)

CTO only

Written justification filed in decision log. Reason, scope, and time limit of override must be stated explicitly.

24 hours post-decision



11C — Rejection and Return

A rejected submission must receive a written return note specifying: the checklist item that failed, the nature of the failure, and what a passing revision would look like. Vague returns ('needs more work') are not acceptable. The reviewer is responsible for the quality of their feedback.



The designer or engineer has the right to challenge a return by escalating to the CTO's office within 48 hours. The CTO's decision on any challenge is final for that version.



11D — Non-Compliance Consequences

Code that has not received dual sign-off will not be merged to any branch above feature scope.

Design assets submitted to staging without a completed checklist will be pulled back immediately.

Repeated non-compliance — defined as three or more unchecked submissions within a single sprint — triggers a formal review of the responsible engineer's or designer's onboarding status with respect to this doctrine.

The enforcement log is reviewed monthly by the CTO's office. Patterns of non-compliance inform the quarterly update cycle.



12. Engineering Requirements — Technical Integration




★

NEW IN v1.1 — Mandatory amendment. The original doctrine addressed UI/UX but said nothing about how front-end code must technically support its rules. Without engineering requirements, 'show business rules before error' becomes a design aspiration with no implementation path. This section closes that gap.



Design and engineering are one pipeline. A workflow that a designer specifies correctly but an engineer cannot implement consistently is still a broken workflow. The following technical requirements are binding on all front-end and full-stack work.



12A — State Machine Modelling

Every entity with workflow states must be modelled as a finite state machine in code. Ad-hoc conditional logic scattered across components is not acceptable. The state machine must be the single source of truth for what transitions are possible and under what conditions.



Use XState, a purpose-built FSM library, or an equivalent that produces an explicit state graph.

The state machine must map directly to the workflow model produced in Section 4. Any divergence between the model and the implementation must be documented and reviewed.

State machine definitions must be committed to the repository and reviewed as part of the standard PR process — not embedded invisibly in component logic.



📌

If you cannot draw the state machine as a diagram, you should not be writing the code that implements it. The diagram is the specification. The code is the implementation. Both must exist.



12B — Business Rule Exposure

Business rules that affect the UI — approvals required, thresholds, permission checks, deadline constraints — must be exposed to the front end in a structured, queryable form. They must not exist only as server-side validation that surfaces through error responses.



Rules affecting workflow actions must be available via a /rules endpoint, a context object populated at load time, or an equivalent mechanism agreed with the tech lead.

The front end must consume these rules to render pre-action warnings, disable actions before they are attempted, and explain constraints inline.

Rules must not be duplicated between front-end and back-end logic. The back end is the source of truth; the front end reads and displays.



12C — Status Enumerations

Status values must not be free-form strings defined independently by different components or teams. They are a shared contract between the data layer, the back end, and the front end.



All status values for a given entity type must be defined in a single shared enum or constant file.

Component styling, available actions, and warning states must be derived from these enum values — never from raw string comparisons.

Adding a new status value requires a pull request that touches: the enum definition, the component that renders it, the state machine that transitions to it, and the checklist entry that covers it.



12D — Audit Logging from UI Actions

Every action that changes the state of a record must produce an audit entry. The UI is responsible for passing context that the back end alone cannot infer.



Audit entries must include: actor identity, timestamp, previous state, new state, action identifier, and source screen ID.

Source screen ID must be a stable, human-readable identifier (not a URL) that can be used to trace a state change back to the screen from which it was triggered.

Audit entries are the basis for the lineage and history displays required by Principle 5 and Section 6C. They must be structured accordingly from the moment of implementation — retrofitting audit data is expensive.



12E — Review Gate for Engineering Compliance

The Engineering Lead review step defined in Section 11B must verify the following before sign-off:



State machine exists and is committed to the repository for every entity with workflow states in this submission.

Business rules affecting this screen are exposed via the agreed mechanism — not inferred from error responses.

All status values in this submission are sourced from the shared enum.

Every state-changing action in this submission writes an audit entry with the required fields.

Accessibility requirements in Section 3F have been met and verified.



Appendix A — Approved Reference Implementations




▲

NEW IN v1.1 — These reference implementations were previously embedded in Section 8 as prescriptive patterns. Per independent review, they have been moved here and reclassified: these are examples, not requirements. Deviations are permitted where a written justification is filed at the time of design review.



The patterns below represent known-good implementations of this doctrine. Study them to understand the standard. Do not copy them blindly — every implementation must be justified against its specific workflow.



A1 — Approval Chain Display

Show the full chain as a vertical or horizontal timeline: completed steps (actor, role, timestamp, outcome), current active step (actor, required action, deadline if applicable), and pending steps (actor, role, awaiting). Place the action the current user can take directly below the chain. Do not separate the status from the action into different views.



A2 — Exception Highlighting in Lists

Rows with overdue, blocked, or flagged status must use a distinct background or left-border colour treatment (not only a text label). The exception must be scannable at row level: status label, days outstanding or exception type, and the primary resolution action — all visible without opening the record.



A3 — Record Detail Structure

Lead with: entity name and type, current status with colour treatment, primary metric (amount, score, date). Follow with: key linked records with their own status visible. Then: allowed actions for the current actor. Then: activity timeline or history. Then: secondary metadata. This order reflects operational priority, not data schema order.



A4 — Financial Document Layout

Counterparty block (name, reference, contact). Document header (number, date, terms). Line items with amounts and tax treatment. Running total with tax summary. Lineage block (linked requisition, approvals received). Action bar (approve, reject, pay, export). The document must feel like a document — not a form.



A5 — Inline Form with Consequence Preview

Before the user submits, display a summary of what the system will do: records created, notifications sent, states changed in linked records, irreversible actions flagged. This preview must be generated dynamically from the current input — not static boilerplate text.



Appendix B — Version Change Log




This log records all substantive changes between versions. It is updated with every release and forms the basis for the monthly review cycle discussion.



